Introduction¶

This dataset contains information about movies released from 1960 to 2015. Our goal is to do some analysis to see relationships between its columns. and answer some question. Our questions:

  • Q1: What is the change in each of (genres, popularity, budget, revenue, number of movies produced, number of succeeded and failed movies, vote counts, vote average) through years from 1960 to 2015

  • Q2: What is the most popular months, most months having high budget and revenue ?

  • Q3: Whats is the movie that has the highest popularity of each year since 1960 ?

  • Q4: Whats is the movie that has the highest revenue of each year since 1960 ?

  • Q5: Whats is the movie that has the highest budget of each year since 1960 ?

  • Q6: Whats is the movie that has the highest vote of each year since 1960 ?

  • Q7: What is the genre that has the highest movies released each year?

  • Q8 What is the relationship between vote average and popularity, and btween succeeded movies and popularity ?

    There are many budgets and revenues having 0 , if we remove them we will have 20% of tthe data , this is not correct of course we can not remove all of them , also we can not put the mean instead , we will take it into account when dealing with budgets and revenues.¶

    Lets add month column and simplify genres column and take the first genre only.¶

    In [15]:
    # release_date column has 3 numbers seperated by "/", the first number is of the month

df['month']=df.release_date.apply(lambda x : x.split("/")[0])
    In [16]:
    # convert month column from string to int

df.month = df.month.astype('int')
    In [17]:
    # genres column contains many genres separated by "|" 
# i will make a new column contains only the first genre, i will make col name "genres2"

df['genres2']=df.genres.apply(lambda x : x if x.find("|")==False else x.split("|")[0])

    # lets group our data in term of the release date
# and find the min, max, average, summation of some columns as
# popularity        >>>>    lets find it's min, max, mean, sum
# original_title    >>>>    lets find it's count which indicates how many movies released on this year
# succeeded_movie   >>>>    lets find sum which indicates how many movies succeeded on this year
# budget            >>>>    lets find it's min, max, mean, sum
# revenue           >>>>    lets find it's min, max, mean, sum
# vote_count        >>>>    lets find it's sum
# runtime           >>>>    lets find it's min, max, mean, sum
# vote_average      >>>>    lets find it's min, max, mean
# genres2           >>>>    lets find it's mode

df2 = df.groupby('release_year').agg({'popularity':['min','max','mean','sum'],'original_title':'count','succeeded_movie':'sum','budget':['min','max','mean','sum'], 'revenue':['min','max','mean','sum'],'vote_count':'sum', 'runtime':['min','max','mean','sum'],'vote_average':['min','max','mean'],'genres2':pd.Series.mode})

    ref: https://pbpython.com/groupby-agg.html

    In [25]:
    # add a column to the number of failed movies in each year

df2['failed_movies'] = df2[( 'original_title', 'count')] - df2[('succeeded_movie',   'sum')]
df2['revenue_budget_diff'] = df2[('revenue', 'sum')] - df2[('budget', 'sum')]

    We will need to plot too many bar charts , so its easier to make a function to help me simplifying my code.¶

    In [31]:
    def bar_plot(x, y, x_label, y_label, title, width, color):
    """
    This function saves me 4 lines each time , it plot a bar chart with x_label, y_label, title, width and color.

    Parameters:
    x : x data of bar chart
    y : y data of bar chart
    x_label (string) : x_label of bar chart
    y_label (string) : y_label of bar chart
    title (string) : title of bar chart
    width (string) : width of bars in bar chart
    color (string) : color of bars in bar chart
    
   """
    plt.bar(x, y, width, color=color)
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)
    plt.title(title)

    Q2: What is the most popular months, most months having high budget and revenue ?¶

    In [43]:
    # lets group our data in term of month
# and find the mean and count of some columns as
# original_title    >>>>    lets find it's count which indicates how many movies released on this month
# popularity        >>>>    lets find it's mean
# vote_count        >>>>    lets find it's mean
# budget            >>>>    lets find it's mean
# revenue           >>>>    lets find it's mean
# succeeded_movie   >>>>    lets find it's mean
# runtime           >>>>    lets find it's mean
# vote_average      >>>>    lets find it's mean

df3 = df.groupby('month').agg({'original_title':'count', 'popularity':'mean', 'vote_count':'mean', 'budget':'mean', 'revenue':'mean', 'succeeded_movie':'mean', 'runtime':'mean', 'vote_average':'mean'})

    Conclusions¶

    1. Drama, comedy and action are the most popular genres
    2. Popularity is increasing each year.
    3. Number of released movies is increasing each year.
    4. Number of succeeded movies and number of failed movies is increasing each year.
    5. Budgets and Revenues is increasing by high ratio each year.
    6. Runtime is decreasing each year.
    7. Movies released in months(5,6,7,11,12) having higher popularity than others.
    8. In 2015, Jurassic World got highest popularity, Star Wars: The Force Awakens got highest revenue, Avengers: Age of Ultron got highest budget, The Jinx: The Life and Deaths of Robert Durst got the highest votes, Drama is dominant.
    9. As vote average increases, popularity increase
    10. If a movie is succeeded (revenue > budget), so popularity is probably high.

    Limitations¶

    1. There are many zeros values in important columns like budget and revenue.
    2. There are some null values that when we removed them, our data is affected a little bit.
    3. Genres column contains many genres, we used first genre only and ignore the other.
    4. No information about the census of the world from 1960 to 2015.
    5. No information about the number of cinemas from 1960 to 2015.
